    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A New Ethanol Bill</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Sen E Benjamin Nelson letter on legislation he is co-sponsoring to require that small but growing portion of nation's fuel include renewable fuels like ethanol or biodiesel (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Ethanol Plan Fails to Reduce Use of Gasoline'' (front page, June 21): While many of us are disappointed that the flexible fuel program has not yet realized its full potential, now is not the time to abandon it.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Ethanol Plan Fails to Reduce Use of Gasoline'' (front page, June 21): While many of us are disappointed that the flexible fuel program has not yet realized its full potential, now is not the time to abandon it.</p>
        <p>I have joined with Senators Tom Daschle and Richard G. Lugar on legislation requiring that a small but growing portion of the nation's fuel include renewable fuels like ethanol or biodiesel. Our legislation would create a sustainable environment for private investment in new ethanol production and distribution. The production and use of ethanol would more than triple over the next decade. Americans would benefit from substantial reductions in costly oil imports, reduced hydrocarbon emissions and a revitalized rural economy.</p>
        <p>It is time that Americans decreased dependency on costly imported petroleum, put economic strategies into effect to reduce greenhouse gases, and expanded alternative markets for our farmers and ranchers.</p>
        <p>E. BENJAMIN NELSON  U.S. Senator from Nebraska  Omaha, June 26, 2001</p>
      </block>
